    "title": "The math to 1500: what 700 R&W + 800 Math actually requires",
    "summary": "Turn your target score into a concrete accuracy goal so you know exactly what to train.",
    "body": "# Your target, in raw terms\n\nYour goal: **1500+**, built from **700+ Reading & Writing** and a **perfect 800 Math**. Let’s translate that into accuracy.\n\n## Reading & Writing → 700\n\nTo score around 700 you generally need to:\n- Route into the **hard Module 2** (≈70% of Module 1 correct).\n- Finish near **~85–90% accuracy** across both modules.\n- In rough terms, **miss only a handful** of the scored questions.\n\nR&W points are most often lost on a predictable set of types: **Command of Evidence**, **Transitions**, **Inferences**, and **Rhetorical Synthesis**. Master those and 700 is very reachable.\n\n## Math → 800 (perfect)\n\nThis is the demanding half. For an **800**:\n- You must route into the **hard Module 2**.\n- You can typically miss **only 0–2 questions total** — and on some forms, **zero**.\n\nThat last point reframes the whole task. At this level, your limiting factor usually **isn’t the math** — it’s **careless errors**: a misread sign, a “find x but they asked for 2x,” a units slip. Reaching 800 is as much about **error-proofing** as it is about knowing content.\n\n## How to use this\n\n- Treat **Math like a precision sport**: the content is learnable; the discipline is the work.\n- Treat **R&W like pattern recognition**: learn the question types and their traps, and your accuracy climbs fast.\n\nYour **Study Plan** page turns these targets into a weekly routine. Your **Progress** page shows whether your accuracy is actually where it needs to be."
