    "summary": "At the 800 level the math is easy; the mistakes are the enemy. Here’s a repeatable defense.",
    "body": "# Killing careless errors\n\nIf you already know the math, the gap between a 760 and an 800 is almost entirely **avoidable mistakes**. Treat them as a process problem, not a “be more careful” problem.\n\n## The five errors that cost 800s\n\n1. **Answering the wrong quantity.** They ask for `2x`, you solve for `x` and stop. *Underline what’s actually being asked.*\n2. **Sign slips.** A dropped negative in distributing or moving terms. *Slow down one notch on any line with a minus sign.*\n3. **Misreading the problem.** “At least,” “no more than,” “increased by” vs. “increased to.” *Re-read the final sentence before you commit.*\n4. **Calculator entry mistakes.** Right method, fumbled keystrokes. *Glance at whether the answer is even plausible.*\n5. **Grid-in format errors.** A correct value entered in a form the grid rejects. *Know the entry rules cold (see below).*\n\n## A 20-second per-question checklist\n\nBefore you click the next button, ask:\n- *Did I answer what they asked?* (the quantity, the units)\n- *Does the magnitude make sense?* (estimate first; a tax can’t be larger than the price)\n- *Did I use every condition in the problem?* (unused info is a red flag)\n\n## Use Desmos to remove arithmetic risk\n\nThe built-in **Desmos graphing calculator** can eliminate whole error classes:\n- **Solve equations** by graphing each side and reading intersections.\n- **Find zeros / vertices** of quadratics visually instead of by hand.\n- **Check** an algebraic answer numerically before committing.\n\n## Grid-in (student-produced response) rules\n\n- You can enter **fractions** (`3/2`) or **decimals** (`1.5`) — both are accepted if equivalent.\n- For repeating decimals, **fill the whole entry field** (e.g., `.666` or `2/3`), don’t round short.\n- **No mixed numbers** — write `5/2`, not `2 1/2`.\n- Negative answers are allowed; **percent and $ signs are not** entered.\n\nThe discipline here *is* the points. Build the checklist into every practice set until it’s automatic.",
