    "id": "rw-transitions",
    "group": "Reading & Writing",
    "tag": "R&W · Expression of Ideas",
    "minutes": 4,
    "title": "Transitions: a logic-word playbook",
    "summary": "Transition questions are pure logic. Sort every transition into four buckets and they get easy.",
    "body": "# Transitions are a logic puzzle, not a vocab test\n\nA transition question gives you two sentences and asks for the word/phrase that connects them. The trick: **ignore the answer choices at first.** Decide the *logical relationship* yourself, then pick the word that matches.\n\n## The four buckets\n\nAlmost every transition fits one of these relationships:\n\n1. **Continue / Add** — the second idea extends the first.\n   - *also, furthermore, moreover, in addition, similarly, likewise*\n2. **Contrast / Reverse** — the second idea pushes against the first.\n   - *however, but, yet, nevertheless, on the other hand, in contrast, still*\n3. **Cause / Result** — the second idea follows *from* the first.\n   - *therefore, thus, consequently, as a result, so, hence*\n4. **Example / Restate** — the second idea illustrates or clarifies the first.\n   - *for example, for instance, in other words, that is, specifically*\n\n## The method\n\n1. Read sentence 1. Read sentence 2. **Cover the blank.**\n2. In your own words, decide: *is sentence 2 agreeing, disagreeing, resulting, or illustrating?*\n3. Match to a bucket, then choose the transition in that bucket.\n\n## The classic trap\n\nThe most common wrong answer is a **continuation word where contrast is needed** (or vice versa). If sentence 1 is a positive and sentence 2 is a negative — *light alloy … but brittle* — you need a **contrast** word. Test-writers love offering a tempting “therefore” or “similarly” to catch students who skim.\n\n> Rule of thumb: if you can’t instantly name the relationship, **read one sentence earlier**. The logic is usually set up just before the blank.\n\nNow drill a set while the four buckets are fresh.",
    "practiceCrit": {
      "section": "rw",
      "types": [
        "Transitions"
      ]
    }
