    "summary": "Every comma, semicolon, and colon question reduces to one skill: spotting where a complete thought begins and ends.",
    "minutes": 4,
    "body": "# Boundaries: commas, semicolons, colons, and run-ons\n\nEvery SAT \"Boundaries\" question is testing one thing: **can you tell where one complete thought stops and another begins?** Master one test and you'll get all of these right fast.\n\n## The independent-vs-dependent test\n\nAn **independent clause** can stand alone as a sentence (subject + verb + complete thought). A **dependent clause** cannot.\n\n- *The experiment failed.* → independent (stands alone)\n- *Because the experiment failed* → dependent (leaves you hanging)\n\n**Your move on every question:** read the words *before* the punctuation and the words *after* it. Label each side \"complete\" or \"incomplete.\" The label combination dictates the mark. Words like *because, although, when, while, if, since, that, which* signal a dependent piece.\n\n## What each mark requires\n\n> **Semicolon = period.** It must have a **complete sentence on BOTH sides**. If you can swap in a period and nothing breaks, the semicolon is correct. If either side can't stand alone, it's wrong.\n\n- **Semicolon (;)** — independent + independent. *The data was clear; the team still hesitated.*\n- **Colon (:)** — the part **before** must be a **complete clause**; what follows (a list, explanation, or even one word) does not need to be. *She wanted one thing: proof.* Wrong: *The tools she needed were: a ruler and a pencil.* (\"The tools she needed were\" is not complete.)\n- **Comma + FANBOYS** (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so) — joins two independent clauses. *It rained, so we left.*\n- **Comma alone** — use after a dependent opener or to set off non-essential info, **never** to glue two independent clauses together.\n- **Dash (—)** — flexible; can do a colon's job or pair up like commas.\n\n## Comma splices and run-ons\n\nA **comma splice** is two independent clauses joined by only a comma — always wrong on the SAT.\n\n- Wrong: *The lecture ran long, students started leaving.*\n- Fixes: period, semicolon, comma+FANBOYS, or make one side dependent (*As the lecture ran long, students started leaving.*).\n\n**Trap to memorize:** *however, therefore, moreover, thus, consequently, nevertheless* are **NOT** FANBOYS. A comma before them between two clauses is still a splice. *The plan was risky, however, we approved it* is wrong → use a semicolon: *...risky; however, we approved it.*\n\n## Supplements need matching bookends\n\nNon-essential information (a name, a description, an aside) gets set off with **paired punctuation** — and both marks must **match in type**.\n\n- Two commas: *Dr. Lee, the lead author, presented.*\n- Two dashes: *Dr. Lee — the lead author — presented.*\n- Comma–dash mismatch is always wrong.\n\n**Test it:** delete the middle chunk. If the sentence still reads cleanly, it's a supplement and needs paired punctuation (or none on both sides). If deleting it breaks the meaning, it's essential — no commas.\n\n## Drill routine\n\nThese questions are pure pattern recognition, so train for speed and a clean record:\n\n- Force yourself to **silently label both sides** (\"complete / incomplete\") before looking at answer choices. Don't go by what \"sounds right.\"\n- When two choices seem identical, the difference is usually splice vs. semicolon — re-check that **both** sides stand alone.\n- Log every miss with the *reason* (\"treated a transition word as FANBOYS\"), not just the right answer. On the hard Module 2 path, Boundaries should be near-automatic points — aim for zero misses here so your effort goes to Inferences and Synthesis.",
    "practiceCrit": {
      "section": "rw",
      "types": [
        "Boundaries"
      ]
    }
