    "body": "# Geometry & Trig: Use the Reference Sheet\n\nGeometry and trig are ~5-7 of your 44 Math questions. The content is finite and the formula sheet is open the whole time — so missing these is almost always a careless error, not a knowledge gap. For an 800, you route hard and miss 0-2. That means **automating the formulas you'll retype anyway and slowing down on the trap setups.**\n\n## The reference sheet is a tool, not a crutch\n\nIt gives you: area/circumference of a circle, areas of rectangle/triangle, Pythagorean theorem, the **30-60-90** ($x, x\\sqrt3, 2x$) and **45-45-90** ($s, s, s\\sqrt2$) ratios, volumes (prism, cylinder, sphere, cone, pyramid), and the arc facts ($360°$ in a circle, $2\\pi$ radians, arc sum). It does **not** give you: similar-triangle ratios, circle theorems, or SOH-CAH-TOA. Memorize the gaps; glance at the rest only to confirm.\n\n## Area, volume, angles\n\n- **Volumes**: don't memorize, but know which letters go where. Sphere $\\frac43\\pi r^3$, cone $\\frac13\\pi r^2 h$ — the cone is one-third the cylinder. Watch for **diameter given as radius** (the #1 volume trap).\n- **Angles**: straight line $=180°$, triangle $=180°$, parallel lines cut by a transversal give equal corresponding/alternate angles. Exterior angle of a triangle $=$ sum of the two remote interior angles — a huge time-saver.\n\n## Similar triangles\n\nWhen triangles share angles (parallel sides, a shared vertex, AA), sides are **proportional**. Set up a ratio and cross-multiply. Critical: **area scales with the square of the side ratio.** If sides are $2:3$, areas are $4:9$. Volume scales by the cube.\n\n## Pythagorean theorem & special right triangles\n\nRecognize the common Pythagorean triples on sight — **3-4-5, 5-12-13, 8-15-17** and their multiples (6-8-10). If you see two of those numbers, you have the third instantly without computing. For 30-60-90 and 45-45-90, **read the sheet's ratio and match the given side to the correct position** — don't guess which side is $x\\sqrt2$.\n\n## Circle theorems: arcs, sectors, radians\n\nEverything is a **fraction of the whole circle**:\n\n> $\\dfrac{\\text{central angle}}{360°} = \\dfrac{\\text{arc length}}{\\text{circumference}} = \\dfrac{\\text{sector area}}{\\pi r^2}$\n\nSet up one proportion and solve for whatever's missing. **Radians**: $\\pi = 180°$. To convert, multiply by $\\frac{\\pi}{180}$ or $\\frac{180}{\\pi}$. Arc length in radians is simply $s = r\\theta$, sector area $\\frac12 r^2\\theta$. Know that a full circle $= 2\\pi$, so $\\frac{\\pi}{2}$ is a quarter turn.\n\n## SOH-CAH-TOA and cofunctions\n\n$\\sin = \\frac{\\text{opp}}{\\text{hyp}}$, $\\cos = \\frac{\\text{adj}}{\\text{hyp}}$, $\\tan = \\frac{\\text{opp}}{\\text{adj}}$. The SAT loves the **cofunction identity**:\n\n> $\\sin(x) = \\cos(90° - x)$\n\nSo if a problem says $\\sin(A) = \\cos(B)$, then $A + B = 90°$. This single fact unlocks a whole question type in seconds. Also memorize the exact values: $\\sin 30° = \\frac12$, $\\sin 45° = \\frac{\\sqrt2}{2}$, $\\sin 60° = \\frac{\\sqrt3}{2}$ (cosine reverses the order).\n\n## Tactics that protect the 800\n\n- **Draw and label every figure**, even when one is given. Mark equal angles and known sides.\n- **Use Desmos** for circle equations $(x-h)^2+(y-k)^2=r^2$ and to confirm intersections — but set up trig/proportions by hand; it's faster.\n- **Flag any figure \"not drawn to scale\"** — never eyeball; solve algebraically.\n- **Log every geometry miss**: was it diameter/radius, area-vs-side-squared, or radian conversion? Those three account for most lost points.",
