    "minutes": 4,
    "body": "## Test-Day Logistics & Mindset\n\nThe test is content you've already trained for. The only new variable on test day is *you* — your battery, your nerves, your routine. Lock those down so all your prep actually shows up on the screen.\n\n### The night before & the gear\n\n- **Charge to 100%** the night before and bring your **charger** anyway. Bluebook drains laptops fast; if you find an outlet near your seat, plug in.\n- **Run the Bluebook \"Exam Setup\"** a day or two early. It re-downloads the test and confirms your device passes the check. Doing this at home means check-in is a formality, not a panic.\n- **Bring:** admission ticket, photo ID, charger, an approved calculator (even though Desmos is built in — redundancy), a watch is *not* needed (Bluebook has a countdown timer), and a snack + water for the break.\n- Arrive early. Rushing spikes cortisol exactly when you need a clear head.\n\n### Check-in & the break\n\n- Check-in is per-device: you'll enter codes, the proctor reads a script, then a start code unlocks the test. It can feel slow — that's normal, breathe through it.\n- There's **one 10-minute break** between R&W and Math. **Get up, walk, eat the snack, splash water on your face.** Do *not* discuss questions or touch your phone (a phone violation can cancel your scores). The timer keeps running if you're late back, so watch the clock.\n\n### The routing mindset: a brutal Module 2 is *good news*\n\nEach section is **section-adaptive**. Module 1 is a mixed bag; your performance routes you to an easier or harder Module 2. **The hard Module 2 is the only path to the top of the score range** — the easy one caps R&W/Math near the high-500s to ~650.\n\n> So when Module 2 suddenly feels *harder*, don't deflate. That difficulty is the system telling you that you crushed Module 1. You earned the hard form. Attack it like a reward, not a punishment.\n\nThat reframe matters because the alternative — \"ugh, this is impossible\" — burns time and confidence on exactly the questions worth the most points.\n\n### A calm per-question routine\n\nBuild one repeatable loop and run it every time. It removes decision fatigue and prevents careless errors (your real enemy at the top).\n\n1. **Read the question stem first** (especially in Math) so you read the rest with purpose.\n2. **Commit or flag in ~10 seconds.** If you don't have a foothold, **flag it and move on** — there's no penalty, and a fresh look later is faster than grinding now.\n3. **Eliminate, don't just hunt for the \"right\" answer.** Two wrong answers gone makes the rest obvious.\n4. **Never leave a blank.** Wrong answers don't cost points, so guess on everything before time expires.\n\n### Pacing anchors\n\n- **R&W:** ~71 sec/question (27 q in 32 min/module).\n- **Math:** ~95 sec/question (22 q in 35 min/module). Use Desmos and the formula sheet, but don't over-rely — typing a simple problem into Desmos can be slower than just doing it.\n\nIf you've banked time, **spend it re-checking flagged questions and re-reading Math stems for \"what is it actually asking\"** — that's where 800-level scores are won or lost. Trust your prep, run your loop, and let the adaptive engine hand you the hard form."
